ce:section.ce:para:
The light absorbance characteristics of bare g-C3N4 and the synthesized CDCNs decorated with different percentages of CP-derived CDs were preliminarily evaluated through the UV–Vis DRS technique (Fig. 3
                        ). As shown in Fig. 3a, bare g-C3N4 possesses a strong intrinsic absorption edge at approximately 460 nm, which is in good agreement with previous reports (Gong et al., 2022). The absorption edge position displays an obvious redshift for the CDCNs in comparison to pure g-C3N4 as a result of the strengthening of interfacial structural connections due to CP-derived CD modification (Chen et al., 2021). Moreover, the CDCNs decorated with various percentages of CP-derived CD samples exhibited different enhanced spectral responses in the visible region, and CDCN-20% possessed the strongest visible-light harvesting capability, thus revealing that the loading of CP-derived CDs in CDCN-20% was optimal. Above the optimal CP-derived CDs content, a decrease in light response occurred, hindering visible-light-driven photocatalysis for CDCNs and reducing the generation of photogenerated carriers. In the inset picture, the band gap energy (E
                        g) values of g-C3N4, CDCN-5%, CDCN-10%, CDCN-20% and CDCN-30% are estimated on the basis of the Kubelka–Munk equation to be 2.72, 2.66, 2.61, 2.55 and 2.58 eV, respectively (Zhao et al., 2022). The optimal CDCN-20% has a much narrower band gap width (2.55 eV) than pure g-C3N4, resulting in higher visible-light utilization, which is related to the subband energy levels between g-C3N4 and the CP-derived CDs in the CDCN-20% bandgap. The emergence of the subband energy levels is most likely due to the effect of carbon addition leading to the formation of more charge separation between g-C3N4 and the CP-derived CDs (Liu et al., 2015). The composite formed by the CP-derived CDs and the g-C3N4 interface mediates the band structure and affects the band gap position.
